    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Unplugged, and Smug</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By BARNABY J. FEDER</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Feder, Barnaby J</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sir Richard Branson reckons he was the only one among 141 executives attending Microsoft's recent conference for CEOs who was not affected by 'Love Bug' e-mail computer virus; Branson relies on paper notebooks and an old-fashioned address book; photo (M)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Sir Richard Branson, the self-described ''technophobe'' whose fortune derives from music and airline ventures under the Virgin brand, looked quite at home briefing reporters last week during a break in Microsoft's closed-door gathering for chief executives.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Sir Richard Branson, the self-described ''technophobe'' whose fortune derives from music and airline ventures under the Virgin brand, looked quite at home briefing reporters last week during a break in Microsoft's closed-door gathering for chief executives.</p>
        <p>But while fellow business leaders spoke of the wonders of technology, Sir Richard couldn't help hazarding a guess that he was the only one among the more than 140 executives completely unaffected by the malicious ''I Love You'' program. His secret: he sticks to notebooks (the paper variety) and an old-fashioned address book.</p>
        <p>BARNABY J. FEDER</p>
        <p>PRIVATE SECTOR</p>
      </block>
